description: From Middle English sike, the northern form of Old English sīċ (see sitch) and also from Old Norse sík; both from Proto-Germanic *sīką (“slow flowing water; trickle”). Cognate with Norwegian sik. Compare Scots sheuch.

entries.meaning: (Scotland, Northumbria) A gutter or ditch; a small stream that frequently dries up in the summer.
examples: The wind made wave the red weed on the dike. bedoven in dank deep was every sike.

description: From Middle English siken, from Old English sīcan (“to sigh”), from Proto-West Germanic *sīkan (“to sigh”). Doublet of sigh.

verbs.description: sike (third-person singular simple present sikes, present participle siking, simple past and past participle siked)

entries.meaning: (archaic or Northern England) To sigh or sob.
